>>Tark's war movies (Mirror, Ivan) have any of that going on in them. 
>Something else springs into mind as having the effect on us as a whole 
you
>are referring to. Letiat Juravli (Cranes fly), Idi i smotri (Go and 
look
>(?)), Oni srajalis' za Rodinu (They fought for the Motherland), Sud'ba
>soldata (Solder's fate) etc. Not Tarkovsky, no.
>
>Vladimir

As an outsider, ie neither Russian nor American, I believe there is a 
great difference here. For Americans, WWII was an overseas war which 
cost the lives of thousands of America's finest and demanded a great 
national effort. For the Soviets, on the other hand, the "Great 
Patriotic War" meant, by conservative accounts, more than 20 million 
Russian, Ukranian and Byelorussian dead and an enemy that despised all 
things Slav and was ready to enslave or annihilate a whole nation.

All this being said, and from word of mouth as I have never been in 
Russia, there is a hint of nostalgia in veteran reunions, where battles 
are often recalled and old timers shake their heads at today's youth.

Regarding the movies, I agree with Vladimir and the Russian movies he 
mentions. By itself, the piano-playing scene in "Cranes Fly" is worth 
the price of admission. For a good insight of the horror that war meant 
to the Russians, I recommend "Come and See" (or Go and Look).

As  for American movies, Slaughterhouse 5 and Catch 22 are the only ones 
that come to mind that are devoid of the "simbad" syndrome. I'm sure the 
List can point out some more.

Nice to have all of you back.


Pablo

