<<  Is there
 any movie or a tangible piece of art to help change/solidify that
 impression ('Saving private Ryan'?) and to better comprehend your
"nostalgia"? >>

I'll do some checking and get back to you with specific titles but I can
certainly support the idea of a nostalgic view of WW2 with considerable
evidence:

At a wedding in Winnemucca, Nevada, three summers ago, I listened in on an
evening's worth of conversations between gentlemen ranging in age from 40-65
(appx.).  They spoke with noticeable frequency of "the" War, when we fought
the good fight, when we were lifted out of our Great Depression, etc.  I was
able to join in a few times because what I'd learned in school (I got
excellent marks on the big tests in US History, thought I recall little) fit
in with this.  After some time and distance, wars settle down into a more-or-
less standard character, that defined by the victor.  We won, therefore we are
nostalgic for a time when we did things right.  It even makes sense, kind of,
unlike current events.

But I'll ask around, like I said, and get back to you from a cinematic
perspective.

Sarvenaz
