Pablo

<< I have noticed that ever since some people started posting messages in 
 Spanish (and latinized Russian), most of you have stopped posting which 
 is a great pity, at least to me. Bear in mind that this is no War of the 
 Tongues, but rather that many people simply cannot write confidently - 
 or at all -  in a foreign language. >>

Yes, I suppose I was a bit intimidated. Not so much because I saw this as a
War of Tongues. I am, in the worst sense, a prisoner of English. I could not
comment upon the Spanish/Russian postings and did not want to seem to be
hostile by ignoring them and writing in English. Not that silence has been
much of a solution, either. Quite right.

I have read through most of the Turovskaya book--it seemed to be a bit heavy
on the worshipping at times, but still well worth the read. I would strongly
recommend the Petrie book (The Films of Andrei Tarkovsky: A Visual
Fugue--something like that). Still, any book on Tarkovsky is of some value,
there are still so few.

As to Thomas' idea that MIrror and Ivan could be seen as linked . . . I don't
know. There are some possible links thematically speaking (war and innocence,
youth, etc.). Both films have extensive treatment of mothers--idealized dream
sequences, etc. Beyond that I can't think of anything especially
fascinating--anyone else want to take a crack at it?

Seamus
