In a message dated 98-09-23 11:04:19 EDT, you write:

<< As  for American movies, Slaughterhouse 5 and Catch 22 are the only ones 
 that come to mind that are devoid of the "simbad" syndrome. I'm sure the 
 List can point out some more.
  >>

Also: "A Midnight Clear", "Mother Night" (both by the same director--the
latter, like Slaughterhouse Five, an adaptation of Vonnegut). For the most
part, I think that it was Vietnam that took the gloss off of war for
Americans--in fact, it is notable that most of these films were made during
the Vietnam Era or were based on books written in that same era--WWII became a
metaphor for the current war. M*A*S*H* did the same thing with Korea and
Breaker Morant (an Australian film) did the same with the Beor War. In as
sense, then, all of these films are arguably Vietnam war films.  

While not a war film "The Best Days of Our Lives" is an unusually frank film
about the post-war situation for soldiers returning from WWII--a situation
that, in part, lead to the so-called Beat Generation. 

Seamus
